Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 countries of the euro zone, inflation was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was registered, as reported by the statistical office of the EU in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have assumed only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the Leitzsins. In their discretion, the interest rate cut, rising commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment would encourage the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least just under the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a quandary: inflation must be "agreed" in order to rule out the need for action at a later date.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a record twelve-year high in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Responsible for the rise in inflation in the Eurozone are the increased food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat prices rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Edible oil and dairy products also rose considerably in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate, but put the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup locates government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers grew considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while support for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
Among voters loyal to the party, the difference is clear thanks to the strong determination of opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) are opposed to one-fifth (20 percent) approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, the MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry hurdle: they come to two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low, overall economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who rate the country's economic situation as "decidedly bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it "pretty bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about the change in their financial situation.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only one-tenth expect an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents — a historic high — rated the prime minister's work as "rather bad than good."
Thirteen percent of respondents have great trust or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the proportion of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared to 27% distrust of the Fidesz leader.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who believe that dissatisfaction with the prime minister can be brought under control without a change of government.
After the unrest last October, 35% were still in favour of keeping the government and the head of government, but today this share is only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would "certainly" participate, and another 20% would "probably" cast their vote.
By comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would "certainly" go to the polls, another 15% consider their participation "likely". In view of these tendencies, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital daily allowance.
Divided into the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty", the shares of opponents of tuition, practice and hospital fees would even amount to 81, 84 and 89 percent respectively.
Auchan the most expensive, Tesco increases by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trading area have maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Articles in Napi Gazdaság
In the Budaörs trading triangle, the price of the usual Christmas basket of the "Napi" has also increased by 16 percent this year, but price increases of over HUF 1,000 were registered in all hypermarkets.
After prices in the food markets "galloped away" last December, inflation has not been drastic in percentage terms compared to the already high, earlier starting level.
However, it is certainly a deterrent to consumers that what they paid well below HUF 9,000 for last year is not even available for HUF 10,000 this year.
The price of the "Napi" shopping cart exceeded the magic HUF 10,000 mark by at least HUF 91 in the markets studied.
The highest price was 10,573 HUF.
(In 6800 the price was 6,800 HUF.)
Prices for unicum and live fish remained almost at the previous year's level, while prices for turkey breast fillets, nuts and poppy seeds rose sharply.
Prices for flour and bread corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, but Auchan had 1kg of bread rolls for 139 forints.
There was no competitive drop in the price of the product to below 200 forints.
Also surprising here was the price of a two-liter Coca-Cola returnable bottle of less than 200 forints, so the drink including deposit cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, in this year's "Napi" shopping basket comparison, Auchan was the most expensive, and Cora the cheapest.
Our calculations have shown that Cora has increased prices in the "Napi" shopping basket by 15 percent compared to Christmas prices last year, while Tesco and Auchan have each increased by 18 percent.
The difference between last year's cheapest basket and this year's most expensive basket was 12%, while the increase between last year's cheapest basket and this year's most expensive basket was 21%.
The average price increase was HUF 1,480.00.
The average price increase in the previous year was still 1,206.00 forints, but the VAT increase made itself felt in the prices at last Christmas.
It is precisely this process that hit retailers hard: it seems that department stores could not really decide which price range to apply to the individual articles, as the effects of the price increase on consumer behaviour were incalculable.
(If the retailer plans the velocity of a product poorly, he can fall by substantial profits in the price range, which depends on the traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the inflation of the "Napi" basket last year was so radical that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 forints, whereas the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 forints.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forints more than the previous year, and even the cheapest there was a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
A comparison of the last two Christmas seasons showed a catastrophic price increase, the price of daily consumables in the hypermarkets has risen by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily confirm the data from the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some staple foods, the Statistical Office found inflation of more than 30 percent over a period of 12 months.
In addition to flour, this also applies to eggs.)
However, if you take a look at the "Napi" shopping cart, this seems almost impossible for the latter, since the price level of the product, which was already expensive in the previous year, has risen by little more than 10 percent even in the worst case.
Obviously, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than the egg suppliers - after all, they were able to pass on the drastic price increase to the multinationals.
In the golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain; There are constant reports of good years.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer look at the prices at all.
Large quantities are purchased from everything, non-perishable food is sold in pallets.
On Wednesday morning, there were endless queues at the cash register in all three department stores when suddenly the number of customers exploded.
However, the country reports a lower customer frequency, so that many multinationals complain to the pollsters that they can not even achieve the planned turnover, not only for food, but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, savings are being made on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to containing the infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, savings are also being made on disinfectants.
The traumatology department of János Hospital was recently diagnosed with MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
As of December 10 this year, 1094 infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the number of unreported cases is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one-third of people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as strep throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or used improperly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria develop from the well-responding bacteria, which spread quickly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune systems, but also in older or low body weight patients, these bacteria can cause serious infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, said Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks during care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are tested for MRSA when they are admitted to hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals are preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for containing the emergence or spread of the multidrug-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the admitted patients and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance for this examination.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug from developing, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
Among outpatients or primary care patients, microbiological sampling is even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
Savings are made on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by nurses.
This is precisely why hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds are tightly strung together, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately it even happens in the financially less well-off hospitals that savings are made on disinfectants, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that promote the development of infections.
Such infections are demonstrably far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs for health insurance companies, so they are being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
According to initial indications, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of the emergence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
Death Leader Police Chief Was Not Drunk
In the case of the fatal car accident caused by the police chief of the XXII district, the official report is now available.
The now-retired police chief of the XXII district, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was neither drunk nor under the influence of drugs, Attila Morvai, the press spokesman for Budapest's chief prosecutor's office, said on Friday after the official report on the case was presented.
The report confirmed the results of the initial investigation, according to which the police chief had not consumed alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
The former police chief turned into Kossuth Lajos Street in his own car in the XXII district and ran over a 55-year-old man who crossed the street at an unmarked place.
(According to StVO, however, this is not a mitigating circumstance - the driver, even if pedestrians do not cross the road at the zebra crossing, has priority.)
The pedestrian succumbed to his injuries after being admitted to hospital.
According to police reports, the driver suffered a shock, then resigned his functions and asked for retirement.
The Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office has launched its investigation into the incident.
In addition, Attila Morvai mentioned that the former police chief had cooperated with the investigators from the beginning.
A further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements worth a total of EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday. The money is to flow into education, transport and environmental protection infrastructure and the energy industry.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for financing transport and environmental projects financed with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement for EUR 100 million was signed earlier, the current agreement deals with the use of the amorous EUR 200 million.
The sum of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be used for the budgetary financing of education projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary; a decision on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be taken later as part of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the area of innovation, the parties have signed an agreement worth EUR 50 million, which will mainly be used for research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also discussed.
It was agreed that as soon as Hungary has clarified the details of metro financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects worth EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest is EURIBOR-linked, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, commission-free.
Bulgaria, the EU's real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is paying close attention to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys the cheapest market in the EU, which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought-after place for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar are the bestsellers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the very favorable area of Ruse will also attract more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - retail and office space offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfers' paradises, attracting tourists in the other two seasons in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria also want to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while the Black Sea and ski resorts are dominated by Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connections and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are very important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of increasing value in the medium to long term.
Real estate in the capital, however, is becoming more and more expensive, due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are lowest in Bulgaria, but over the past five years there has been an annual price increase of 21 percent.
Inflation in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
A fierce debate is currently underway between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
The other big question of the conference is whether the industrialized countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on assistance to developing countries.
The Adaptation Fund, which is subject to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be administered by a 16-member council, presumably at the UN's Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be read in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leadership in global climate action and reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister stated that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (compared to 1990 levels), regardless of whether the "post-2012 agreement" was successfully reached or not. The Union would even be prepared to push for a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialised countries in the world or developing countries are also prepared to meet their obligations to the best of their ability and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor emphasized that the target of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its 15 member states at the time, had already committed itself to a minus of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, according to the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be ready within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also stressed by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee of the UN that was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, in its latest report.
This would delay emission reductions and increase the Earth's average temperature by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, with extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video portal in order to increase popularity.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Since March 2006, special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban on the Internet, reports the BBC.
The footage, shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets, is checked at the Kandahar air base and then sent to London, where it is posted on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, and their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defence headquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeepers (MNFIs) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of the foreign missions.
Such published propaganda is almost free compared to traditional television commercials, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, as they confirm the raison d'être of the government's military measures in their own way.
Americans advertise with games
But the army also has to fight against amateur footage that, in addition to the carefully edited, censored footage, also makes it onto the Internet - such as those showing the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are only talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Incidentally, numerous videos shot in action from the war zones in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "species" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
Christmas party with raffle and pogatsche in the ministries
Labour Minister Mónika Lamperth is by no means squeamish: instead of a Christmas party, she organises a working conference at which her employees can end the year 2007 with coffee and gossip.
Some ministries celebrate with live music, others conjure up Christmas spirit with raffles or toasts to the hearts of civil servants.
Party, Christmas spirit, concerts and buffet - that's how power celebrates.
The Christmas fever has already reached the offices.
The largest Christmas party of a ministry will be held this year in the defense department, but not the employees of the ministry are expected.
At the "Christmas Party of the Orphans" children of fallen soldiers are given presents, at the "Mission Celebration" family members of soldiers currently stationed abroad are entertained, but there is also a reception for the press.
The department is providing around 25 million euros for the celebrations.
Compared to other departments, the National Agency for Development (NFÜ) and the Ministry of Economy and Transport are going overboard.
The 4.32 million forint Christmas party of the Ministry of Economy will be held in the House of the Future, about 350 of the 600 employees are expected.
While the focus of the festivities will be on Christmas, there will also be live acts and a raffle.
The National Agency for Development (NFÜ) held its 4.7 million forint Christmas party on Wednesday at the House of the National Council of Justice (OIT), with concerts and a banquet.
The hall rent amounted to 1 million forints, the rest was spent on the more than 400 invited guests.
According to our information, a department of the NFÜ is also invited to another Christmas party organized by the Hungarian Economic Development Centre (MAG Zrt) with EU funds.
For the celebration, the building of the comedy theatre ("Vígszínház") was rented.
MAG Zrt has not confirmed this information because we have not reached the responsible persons.
Why the suit?
The OIT building was open not only to the guests of the NFÜ, but also to the Ministry of Justice and Police, which held the Lucia Ball there instead of a Christmas party on 7 December.
They did not have to pay rent to the OIT for the use of the premises.
Around 500 visitors came to the ball.
The festivities were opened with a speech by the minister, after the dinner there was live music to dance.
At the request of [origo] it was said: There was no ball gown or suit obligation at the ball.
The ministries of health, labour, and self-government are each preparing for a puritanical celebration.
The Ministry of Health organizes the celebration for the employees in their own four walls for around 400,000 forints.
Labour Minister Mónika Lamperth officially does not invite her employees to a Christmas party, but to the conference at the end of the year.
It is expected that there will be about 180 guests, who - according to the press department - will only be served coffee and poatsche, so the celebration goes out with 350,000 forints.
Minister of Self-Government Gordon Bajnai and his colleagues will simply toast in the ministry's auditorium.
The Ministry of Finance (PM) organizes a Christmas party in its own ballroom, to which 436 employees are expected.
The expenses were estimated at 2,500 forints per capita - for this money there is a buffet reception followed by a toast.
Since the beginning of János Veres' term of office, PM staff have celebrated in this way every year.
However, there will be no real party atmosphere - not only because of the official speech of the minister but also because the celebration has been scheduled for the afternoon.
The Ministry of Agriculture invites you to a New Year's reception on 20 January, the Christmas party of the Ministry is cancelled this time.
One hundred guests are invited to Vajdahunyad Castle in the City Park ("Városliget"); According to the department, the expenses are estimated at 1,000 forints per guest.
According to the press department, it will be a very simple reception, to which only foreign diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
The receptions, which are held every year, traditionally begin with a short speech by the minister and end with a reserved feast.
As the corresponding press offices report on [origo] request, there will be neither a Christmas party at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs nor at the Ministry of Education.
When asked about the costs of the Christmas party, the press department of the Ministry of the Environment could not provide any information.
In any case, more than 400 guests were invited to the celebration, which is held in the Museum of Decorative Arts.
More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Federation of Trade Unions will form their coordinating committee on Friday for the indefinite strike that begins on Monday.
On Saturday, a large protest assembly will be held, on Monday - on the day of the referendum on the health insurance law - the work stoppage begins.
Significant traffic disruptions are expected due to strikes, as rail traffic will be almost completely suspended, and the Budapest Public Transport Authority (BKV) will also strike until 1 p.m.
Details of Monday's strike will be announced jointly by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee will also be formed, which will be responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A large protest rally will be held on Saturday, and from Monday onwards, all organisations that have joined the strike will stop work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike that began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law was not defined.
If the National Council does not adopt the Health Insurance Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call to strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet to discuss how to proceed.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that it comes only in the late evening hours, or even at midnight to the vote on the health insurance law.
Due to the strikes starting on Monday, considerable traffic disruptions will have to be expected: the railway workers will stop work indefinitely, in the morning the majority of public transport and more than half of the Volán companies will be at a standstill.
At the same time, there will be motorway closures in one direction in many places.
The call for a strike has been followed by numerous trade unions and civil organisations - the list of participants is constantly updated on the League website.
Some organisations have announced strikes indefinitely, others are planning a temporary work stoppage.
By Thursday afternoon, no agreement had been reached between Hungarian Railways MÁV and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers VDSZSZ on sufficient services, although more and more people are travelling by train around the Christmas holidays.
According to previous reports, there are strikes at BKV from the start of operations until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 and 9 a.m., the LIGA unions for electricity and heat energy stop work for four hours, and the teachers' union bwz. the Democratic Teachers' Union have called 2- or 2-8-hour strikes.
The Hungarian Medical Association goes on strike at different times across the country, while the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Care Workers, a subsidiary of SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and present a new concept for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
Demand number three is that eligible professionals should be given access to the early retirement scheme before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer made by the Ministry of Transport concerning the secondary lines and is now calling for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases state risk
According to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a conflict, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "Public figures have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups, who have now based their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian antagonism".
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, promote extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The Research Institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media, have "significantly damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously on the upswing, so that since the summer of 2007 several organizations calling themselves "National Self-Defense Association" have been founded.
"What these groups have in common is that they define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly bragging about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (civil protection, national defense, law enforcement), citing the unsuitability of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further: All this is done according to the method that tries to camouflage various political aspirations based on the political and party disenchantment of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of association therefore serve not only to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration with the court - it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also represent a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, and some ultra-nationalist politicians from neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirmation of their own anti-Hungarian policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region," it said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central-Eastern Europe, thus the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background to the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Polyana).
The BNU took the incidents as an opportunity to establish the National Guard, arguing that the organization's goal was "national protection."
