Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, public holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of rescheduling the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year will bring us fewer such days.
In the EU and America, too, "holiday" is understood differently.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and non-working days.
Non-working days are usually church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: Both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve revelers can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The national holidays are March 15, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, the commemoration day of the Revolution of 1956.
On 20 August the founding of the state is celebrated, on 1 May the work, on 1 and 2 November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the long weekends, however, is that we have to work or go to school on the Saturdays before.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, should finally be processed, has been determined for many years by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants.
The only exceptions are companies and institutions in which operations continue without interruption, i.e. even on public holidays.
This year, the work order is only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: From 24 December, life in this country literally stops, as most people take time off for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the specially cancelled holiday.
Next year, more holidays will fall in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer rescheduling of working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around Labour Day so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday 26 April will be a working day so Friday 2 May can be a rest day.
The second rescheduling is related to the holiday on 23 October: On Saturday, 18 October, Friday, 24 October will have to be processed in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely dominated by the holidays, after from 24 December everything remains and stopped, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six daunting little things to annoy work colleagues
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: They bring "color" into everyday life at work.
The only question is whether you get used to these small inconveniences, or do you better face the challenge and try to deliberately avoid these misleading, annoying situations for others.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called" - says a colleague.
That you missed a meeting as a result?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and ruefully admitting that you forgot to get the message across (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the matter is dismissed with an apology.
Before you get caught up in embarrassing excuses, you should think about what you can use to give your colleagues truly unpleasant moments and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Borrowed something that doesn't belong to you?
There's hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office supplies, or the phone, but it's not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it is gone?
Or will the lost ballpoint pen be discovered on a colleague's desk?
Without questions, you should not borrow anything from your colleagues, because they are rightly annoyed when they realize that something has come away.
So, don't put envelopes or post-its from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you: none there anymore, if you need it urgently.
Gossip about the private lives of colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop gossip that has already been created.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
If possible, you should not tie the information (or assumptions) about the private life of your colleagues to everyone's nose!
And if someone does open up and tell us his innermost secret, we should not abuse this trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave instead of aligning those who are not present, even if others also know about the problems of the colleague.
Reported sick for no reason?
If you call the office to call in sick, citing excruciating headaches, because you feel unwell, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: Your own work, urgent errands, projects with fixed deadlines must now be done by your colleagues instead of you.
So don't play alike your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you will not make it to the office the next day, or that something could interfere, which is why you have to stay at home, you should report it in good time so that neither your colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Humming, giggling, talking on the phone
You are currently engrossed in your work, but are suddenly disturbed by the loud giggles of your colleagues?
Unintentionally overheard a telephone conversation that should not have been heard?
You should not annoy your colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (which you lead over their heads), trampling, constant scolding or nagging.
All this can be very disturbing, even if they are not immersed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Are others always to blame?
If a project is not finished on time, if you forgot to send an important letter or important messages, you should not blame others for your own forgetfulness!
If possible, you should not talk yourself out of the chaos in the office or the noisy colleagues!
It's best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were also affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake, or how to make up for what was missed, is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like at home?
Training pants and slippers: Comfortable for home, but has no place in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress accordingly in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
Want to make it right for everyone - or how to become uninteresting for others
Stop and go traffic, the car in the middle of the morning traffic jam.
A strange melody comes out of the radio: the sound of a violin paired with electronic effects.
I turn the volume up.
The tempo changes, the bass comes to the previous sounds, and as a real sound jewel a female choir.
It is the song "Wings of Love" by Zagar, which sounds on mr2.
