The appearance of Yonderboi, many new and exciting productions from the domestic digital underground scene are slowly contributing to a change in the overall picture, and even if the garage rock with its guitar equiche is "in" again, the domestic electropop proves: There is something new under the sun.
Balázs Zságer started in Pécs, played in the band Yonderboi, before he - perhaps because an inn cannot tolerate two pipers - began to go his own way.
The breakthrough with his project (Zagar) and his music, which merges elements of jazz, electronic, and pop, he made but only after the request to compose the soundtrack to a film, he had been approached (e.g.
"Szezon" by Ferenc Török).
The formation, which had initially performed in smaller clubs, only became known to the wider audience when the magazine "wan2" ranked their first album from 2002 among the top 50 domestic albums and named Zagar, together with Yonderboi, almost the only trendsetter marketable in the West.
Without a doubt, Zagar and his band were "trendy", but nobody cared if they liked to wear this brand.
The band reacted as it should: with a new, even better album.
The new album entitled "Cannot Walk Fly Instead" could open up new paths for them, but the title already expresses the desire for continuity with the Pécs years.
The expression comes from the time when Balázs Zságer was still on the road with another band.
The airy, flying allusion would also be fine, but in addition to the ethereal character of the music, the louder guitar - corresponding to the zeitgeist and the trends - the influences of rock'n'roll stand out.
With these songs, the singer György Ligeti, who lives in England and works with the band "The Puzzle", introduced himself at the premiere in Millenáris.
One song from the album has even made it to a radio hit - mr2 Petőfi, who has recently started broadcasting pop music from morning to night, has successively set the catchy tune for listeners with the number "Wings of Love", which was recorded with the participation of six local singers ("Underground Divas").
So everything is fine (?).
The hvg.hu asked Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: This new hit raises the question: To what extent is your music reserved for a certain layer?
Balázs Zságer: The term "layer music" doesn't mean much to me.
In my opinion, there are two castes in pop music, not mainstream and underground, or alternative and pop, but commercial and honest.
Even so-called alternative or underground music can be shallow and meaningless, but it can also be produced only for sale that turns it into commercial music.
Even a good pop number can arise from an honest motive.
The receptiveness of the listener also works according to this principle, independent of languages and national borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference in the openness of Hungarian and foreign audiences towards your music?
B. Zs.: Abroad, especially west of us, pop music has a greater tradition.
Not only teenagers or twens go to concerts, but also the older audience.
They follow the trends in pop music that are happening around them much more closely because they also consider them a part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What role does the audience play in your work?
Is it important who, where, how many listen to your music?
B. Zs.: Of course it's a good feeling to see that more and more people are coming to our concerts.
But we never composed for the market.
For us, music is not created to serve a purpose, but for a reason.
The role of the audience is mostly noticeable at the concerts, where there is already a mutual interaction, but this only exists in the intangible changes of the moment.
Nevertheless, I noticed one thing: If you want to please everyone, you are no longer interesting.
hvg.hu: How far would you like to follow Yonderboi's example?
He is on the road as a soloist and has built his career more in the West.
B. Zs.: We don't really go his own way, quite apart from the fact that people always try to interpret this into our music.
We see ourselves more as team players who trust in each other's musical presence and let it unfold.
In the beginning, of course, comparisons of our work with Yonderboi's were inevitable, as several of us come from his band and have taken a different path.
hvg.hu: In the charts of mr2 Petőfi "Wings of Love" is at the top.
Many have only heard the name Zagar in connection with this number.
Was the opening deliberately staged with a slightly more popular style towards a wider audience?
B. Zs.: We had no plans to write a hit that would serve as a driving force for the album.
This song is about more.
It was intended as the finale of the album, with which we wanted to dissolve the sound and the somewhat more difficult themes.
hvg.hu: How did you choose the six singers?
Why her, what was the guiding principle?
B. Zs.: The basic idea was to make a gospel-like choir.
Then came the idea of assembling the choir from talented soloists from the local music scene.
This is how the six-member choir came into being - Sena, Edina Kutzora, Judie Jay, Bori Péterfy, Enikő Hodosi [Neo], Juci Németh - which we then aptly christened "Underground Divas".
hvg.hu: Did you want the song to be the same, or did the girls help shape it?
B. Zs.: The number had been around in the instrumental version for a long time, but when the material for the album was finished, we thought that this number "needs something".
The chord sequence literally demanded a singing voice.
I sang the melody that same night, later the girls learned it.
It all came practically right away and frighteningly spontaneous.
I can remember, I was quite electrified at the time, but it also took the "Divas".
With my voice alone, the song would never have been so powerful.
hvg.hu: Both on the record and at the concert you had the impression that the girls were in the background.
There is no solo part (apart from the short solo by Judy Jay), they have no role of their own, sing completely together and are not louder than the music, so their singing is not only accompanied by the music.
They were also at the back of the stage.
Is it intentional?
B.Zs.: The fact that they were at the back was due to purely technical problems.
However, we deliberately did not want to give them solo roles.
The number is also about forgetting your ego a little, forgetting who came from where and where we went, let's just let these particular wings, the wings of love, lift us up.
I would like others to feel this euphoric state that we felt when the song was created.
hvg.hu: Which was the most elaborate song?
B. Zs.: In the musical creative work actually none at all, there were rather more difficult tasks in mixing.
For example in "Dorian Gray's Dilemma", in which I play on a concert piano, or in "Rock'n'Roll Goes To The Girls", where the groove did not work for a long time, but gradually everything came together, like a puzzle.
hvg.hu: What is your favorite number from the new album?
B. Zs.: That changes constantly with the concerts and also now that I have "let go" of the album.
Currently it is "Prophet Is A Fool", "Escape From The Earth" and the number "Never The Same".
