Czech Republic has the chance to get to 365 billion
Czech ministers and representatives of the European Commission yesterday signed a total of nine development programmes, through which the Czech Republic can reach 14 billion euros (about 365 billion crowns) over the next few years.
This is about half of the sum that the Czech Republic can receive from Brussels between 2007 and 2013.
About 125 billion crowns come from seven regional development programmes.
Czech companies will be able to receive about 100 billion crowns from the "Enterprise and Innovation" programme.
Most of the money, about 150 billion, will go into transport expansion.
The transport programme is the largest development programme and comprises up to 22 per cent of the funds that the Czech Republic can receive from the fund.
This money increases the budget of the State Transport Infrastructure Fund, which will have 90.8 billion at its disposal next year.
The "Enterprise and Innovation" programme is designed to help entrepreneurs and firms attract funds for innovative ventures.
The aim is to gain finance for the introduction of new technologies, for business research, but also for the introduction of more effective organisational methods.
In terms of money acquisition from EU funds to date, the Czech Republic has been one of the least successful among the new accession countries.
