Banks want to overcome the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis on the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will reach the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, the banks auction off interest rates at which they are willing to lend each other money.
For example, the American Fed is sending $40 billion to auction, and loosening another $24 billion for the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to avert or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This move is intended to address the economy's biggest difficulties, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in a report for his clients.
"Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the U.S. from 65% to about 50%," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unserviced loans, mostly in the United States.
Analysts expect further billions in losses.
"Central banks must have been really afraid of what else could do when they decided to do this," said ABN Amro's chief economist Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he said.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, lending will also become more expensive for their customers.
That would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into recession, potentially affecting economic growth around the world.
Central banks decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used in lending money between banks.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend each other money, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK had cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"This will have the same effect as a further cut in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this move by central banks is heating up the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the fall of the US housing market.
