600,000 people failed to exchange their driving licences
600,000 drivers missed the deadline to exchange their old driving licence, which expires at the end of the year.
Today is the last day when you can apply for the exchange so that the authorities manage to issue a new driving licence by the end of the year.
The ministry, however, does not fear that after New Year, hundreds of thousands of drivers without a valid driving license on the roads.
According to the authorities, mainly those who no longer want to drive have not exchanged their driver's license.
While small towns report a sharp drop in interest in exchanging driving licences, the capital's offices are being inundated with applications, and interest in the exchange grew even further this week.
The city administration handles around 2000 customers every day.
You have to queue for about half an hour.
In Prague, about 140,000 drivers have not yet exchanged their driving licences.
The issuance of a new driving licence takes 20 days.
But it is possible to apply for the issuance with a shortened period of five days.
In this case, however, the driver must pay 500 crowns.
Motorists who fail to complete the mandatory exchange by the end of the year and drive off without a valid driver's license will face a fine from January.
The culprit pays a maximum of 2000 crowns.
However, the police can also leave it with a warning for the violation.
In case of violation, the penalty can rise to 2500 crowns.
According to previous information, the municipality may also impose a penalty on those who do not drive at all.
He could, it was said, face a fine of as much as 30,000 crowns.
The ministry has already called on the authorities to show leniency and impose a maximum fine of 1000 crowns.
According to the spokesman for the Ministry of Transport, Karel Hanzelka, no one is threatened with a thousand-crown fine.
The driving licence is a document in which anyone can decide whether he wants to possess it or not.
It is not an identity card that everyone, and indeed a valid one, must have.
People who no longer want to drive should surrender their driver's license.
It is sufficient to take him to the competent municipal office or send him there by registered mail.
At the end of the year, driving licences issued between 1964 and 1993 expire.
However, motorists will gradually have to exchange other types of driving licences.
People with driving licences from 1994 to 2000 have three years left to exchange them.
Driving licences issued between 2001 and 2004 expire in December 2013.
According to Hanzelka, this involves about 2.6 million more driver's licenses.
