Cuba - most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it really is an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will come true if you choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is calm like a pond.
Palm trees and all-inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream, and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place ever seen by a human eye.
Havana once became a warehouse or transit warehouse of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was founded at the very end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the bosses of the American Mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, skyscrapers grew, cars drove along the wide boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought an estate in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and had his yacht in Cojímar.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
Hotel Nacional's bar serves cocktails to your liking.
And the cult cars of the fifties drive around in Havana to this day, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Havana may be very run-down, especially its oldest part, but nowhere else can you find so many wonderful colonial sights in the vicinity as here.
Other places are currently being spruced up, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a quirk that is unique in the world and attracts above all railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam- and diesel-powered narrow-gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives whose peers have long been in museums elsewhere.
Destinations
The majority of visitors to Cuba do not miss the most important places.
So you don't have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
It only remains to mention that in the already mentioned estate of Hemingway there is a museum, which those who like this writer should not miss.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, fertile soil accumulated in their cavities, through which even weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet it when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spaniards colonized the island.
The trade in slaves and sugar brought her fame and fortune.
The wealth was embodied in the pretty beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountains, is such a remote place that even in the fifties of the last century there was no road to connect the area with the rest of the country.
This isolation contributed to the fact that it went unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was happy that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon to visit Trinidad, it is worth visiting interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón beach or the "Valley of the Sugar Factories".
In the evening you should go to the Casa de la Música, which comes alive after dark and where the music is not silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the far east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Certainly, this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads that lead there from Guantánamo have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape hardly touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included in its World Heritage List by UNESCO thanks to the untouched nature there.
This is where the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the Cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the voyages of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, now Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about Santeria, an African religion professed by the descendants of slaves, you could write many pages about all this.
But, as they say: Better look with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans claim.
According to the United States, too few soldiers and the lack of necessary equipment are influencing the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, NATO should draw up a concrete plan for the next few years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going according to their ideas, the representatives of the countries stationed in the south of the country agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland.
In addition to growing opposition from the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, called on NATO forces to be more active, Britain sees the priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and intensifying development aid.
"There is a sense of progress in Afghanistan, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is to enable the inhabitants to start developing the economy and security themselves," British Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
According to the American army, the activity of the Afghan insurgents has reached its highest level in five years.
The number of violent actions has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, in the southern province of Helmand by as much as sixty percent.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops stationed in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the allies have reached an absolute limit in terms of organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they are calling for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train the Afghan units.
"We're going to have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the near future and how we can achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop made a similar statement today.
