The government had planned to go into debt this year with 159.2 billion cones.
At the beginning of December, however, thanks to the better development of the state budget policy, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion.
The Czech Republic's public debt rose to CZK 842.7 billion by the end of September.
Within the first nine months of this year, they rose by 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, they have fallen by 13.4 billion.
The Ministry of Finance thus confirmed its data on the national debt from the beginning of October.
Each Czech owes 84,000 crowns.
Over the entire past year, the state went into debt by more than 111 billion crowns.
"So far, it seems that thanks to the lower deficit for next year, we may not exceed the one trillion crown mark until 2009.
Next year, the debt should be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns," David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, told iHNed.cz.
