Better than expected
The financing strategy and the handling of the national debt for 2007 show that the government had planned to raise 159.2 billion crowns for this year.
At the beginning of December, however, thanks to the better development of the state budget policy, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion crowns.
This amount is mainly due to the government budget deficit, which will apparently reach 76 billion crowns this year instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
In addition, there are a maximum of 13.3 billion crowns for the consolidation agency, a ten billion reserve to pay pensions, the financing of government bonds for 43 billion and instalments for the bonds at the European Investment Bank in the amount of 1.8 billion.
For giving a teddy bear a name, she was brought before a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been accused in Sudan of insulting Islam, was sentenced on Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and then expulsion.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to name a teddy bear Mahomet, although any representation of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be flogged.
After parents of students complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at Khartoum's Unity High School, was picked up at her home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports principal Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Muhammad as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Muhammad is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My Name is Mohammed.
The bear itself did not carry a shield with this name, but the problem is quite simply that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she had never done anything to offend her to a religious faith, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion it was just an innocent mistake.
An opinion shared by many of the teacher's students, who describe her as very attentive to her students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Consider that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common middle name in Great Britain, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of reverence to the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
On Wednesday, at the last negotiating session in Vienna, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
In the end, the failure
Kosovo's Serbs and Albanians ended a sixth and final discussion session Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome their controversies over the separatist province's future status.
It is regrettable that the parties could not come to an agreement on the status, said European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was at stake, its American counterpart, Frank Wilsner, called on Belgrade and Pristina to honour their commitments to preserve peace and to continue talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, indicating that there are clear tensions.
End of conciliation on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which brings together the European Union, the US and Russia, will meet for the last time on Monday in Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the province, which is 90% Albanian-speaking, could become clearer when Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final negotiating session since the Troika was mandated by the UN last August to remediate.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mandate to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the granting of Kosovo's independence at the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this end date.
Russia was and remains an advocate of a negotiated solution, an amicable solution, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration, Western countries consider independence under EU supervision to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is prepared to announce them unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, announced the President of the Autonomous Authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, at the hotel in Baden, where these last-chance negotiations have been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regret.
He added, however, that the autonomy plan proposed by Belgrade belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.
