Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, believed that compromise should always be sought and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence for the province.
Belgrade says that it is particularly afraid of a "domino effect" in a region that is still weakened by the wars of independence of the 90s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision would be taken solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally has veto power.
Kosovo's parliament will have the last word
Only a decision from the ranks of the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia, Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.
Fatmir Sejdiu told journalists that Kosovo's parliament would have the final say on status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population would take place in coordination with Western countries.
Bush elicits an agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
At the opening of the international peace conference held under his leadership in Annapolis, Maryland, on Tuesday, President Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to begin negotiations immediately to find a final settlement to the 60-year-old disputes between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do everything he could to help them conclude a peace treaty before the end of 2008.
