The White House chief stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian authorities under Abbas ultimately seek a peace treaty that would resolve all outstanding issues without exception, including the central issues.
This term encompasses the three major problems around which the disputes between Israelis and Palestinians mainly revolve: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of the Arab refugees who were expelled from their homes, which is now the State of Israel, in the course of the 1948 conflict.
After the American president, Abbas took the floor and insisted that the upcoming negotiations be conducted comprehensively and thoroughly, and that he provide a settlement on all points, listing Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security, among others.
When Olmert took the floor, he pledged to ensure that the coming ceasefire negotiations would be conducted directly and without interruption and that he would endeavour to conclude them before the end of 2008.
Bush has set the deadline for the end of 2008 to implement his vision of two states, one Palestinian and one Israeli, existing side by side.
Saudi Arabia has revealed that it received an assurance to that effect from Bush before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a great success for Washington, has launched a plan adopted by all Arab countries offering peace to Israel in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis represents a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, especially because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central aspects, says the Saudi prince in his interview with the Saudi-funded Arabic-language daily.
