Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to carry out the spectacular repair of a defective solar panel, which is essential for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has achieved several records due to its duration, the distance of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized and the tools made by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem occurred Wednesday when astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the space shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that will soon house European and Japanese science labs.
