So the crew's second task was to move a 17.5-ton module for generating electricity via solar panels, which was already on the ISS, to bring it into its final position.
After moving it, the crew set about restructuring the module's solar panels, which have a wingspan of 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be unfolded like accordions, was damaged by a trapped cable over a length of about one meter.
The restructuring was stopped so as not to damage the collector even more.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to leave the space shuttle Discovery for a patrol and then repair another solar panel whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-meter remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle, which had been attached to that of the station, to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Tall, resistant, very dexterous, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was therefore selected to operate on the injured solar panel.
After inspecting the damage, he cut the faulty cable and attached a kind of rails to the damaged area.
He was assisted by a second Spacewalker, who remained near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, including Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick wrapped with an insulator to prevent electric shock on the solar panels that generate several hundred volts, had been conceived and tinkered with by the astronauts on board the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully unfolded before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery today, expected to make the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
