A heavy souvenir
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents in the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen over a total length of 27 km, have not yet been inspected, except with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and by name, i.e. by query of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states responsible for its administration – including Germany, France, Israel and the USA – agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
Now that the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been in force since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The historians' access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of the forced laborers, explains Reto Meister, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmate lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labor, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal enquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One should not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, declared in 2006.
