New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is smouldering between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being affected.
Most of Russia's natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) pass through Ukraine, and every dispute between the two nations is watched very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine will have to be charged more, as the company has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This subsequently led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drove up prices drastically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is replenishing its own stockpiles with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
