The National Health Service is expected to carry out pre-employment checks on foreign staff to ensure they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisations to work in the UK.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the Agency does not have jurisdiction to obtain this information outside the UK.
The chief auditor's report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record extract, which helps employers with inspections in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not carried out routinely," the report noted.
Black said Scottish health authorities would follow their pre-employment inquiry guidelines to a high degree, but added: "Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information is available on the number of foreign health service workers."
