A police spokesman said three people have been arrested and that the material is being examined.
He did not confirm whether it was enriched uranium, but said it could have been sold for $1 million (£480,000).
Everything still open
Mitt Romey said he didn't think it was worthy of a presidential candidate to be questioned by a snowman.
Nevertheless, the Republican presidential candidate ultimately agreed to face a debate on YouTube in which ordinary voters record and submit questions on video to broadcast to the candidate.
None of the questions raised on Wednesday night, November 28, were as ridiculous as the snowman questioning Democrats about global warming in the other party's YouTube debate.
But the questions, and the answers, this time accurately reflected the state of the Republican Party as it heads into next year's elections.
It is not known, just like the producers of CNN who supported the debate, who chose the budding candidate YouTube clips to show.
However, in the first half hour of the debate, the longest devoted to a single issue, immigration took centre stage.
The issue is one of the most powerful issues for Republicans.
CNN asked a group of undecided voters to operate a dial when they heard things they liked: The television network noticed spikes in approval as candidates spoke strictly across borders.
The sharpest and longest exchange of the evening was between Rudy Giuliani, the national leader, and Romney, who has moved forward in the decisive polls in Iowa and New Hampshire.
Giuliani is trying to shake off the reputation that he was soft on illegal immigration when he was mayor of New York.
He attacked Romney by accusing the former governor of Massachusetts of hiring illegal immigrants to work at his home.
The two clashed particularly fiercely when questioners asked whether any of the candidates would support an "amnesty" (which would give illegals regular status and the possibility of citizenship).
Lesser candidates such as Duncan Hunter, a California congressman, and Tom Tancredo, a congressman from Colorado, managed to follow up on the issue.
Neither of the two men has a serious chance of winning the nomination, but both remain in the race, perhaps because they hit the immigration slap earlier and harder than others.
At least in the area of immigration, the candidates broadly share the same views: stricter borders, intolerance towards illegal migrants.
This issue, along with fears about toxic toys from China or other concerns about the rest of the world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the differences between liberals and Christian conservatives.
But the debate clearly became problematic when other issues were raised.
Mr. Giuliani was asked why he had supported gun restrictions in the past.
John McCain and Romney debated whether simulated drowning should be considered torture.
One of the questioners asked if the candidates believe every word of the Bible.
This led Giuliani to argue that although the Bible was his favorite book, he might not literally believe the story of Jonah and the whale.
Another questioner asked whether Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee — now, against all odds, in first place in a recent poll in Iowa thanks to his long-standing Christian conservatism — said the death penalty was painful but necessary.
When pressed to see if Jesus would approve of them, he laughed at it and said Jesus was too intelligent to run for political office.
The race remains exceptionally wide open.
Huckabee's rise in Iowa coincides with Ron Paul's recent fundraising successes and his storms of applause in Wednesday's debate.
These two have sprung up out of nowhere because the two wings of the party have not yet been able to agree on one of the better-known and more traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one candidate united the party from the outset and convincingly with a winning message about America's greatness and a wink at both wings of the party.
This time, the party is divided and the outcome is far from clear.
Pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered yet another pit to fall in; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No titles of nobility seem to have been sold, no politician paid Parisian hotel bills, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the revelation that a wealthy businessman concealed donations to Britain's ruling Labour Party of more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under other people's names, and that the party failed to report it, is something that the embattled Gordon Brown would have gotten along without.
Two months ago, when the prime minister evaded the call for an election, stupidly insulting the British intelligentsia by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced this decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly astute deputy leader of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once-feared Brown has evolved from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy bailout of Northern Rock, a struggling bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under attack.
Ill-conceived proposals to amend tax laws have turned business associations against the government.
The loss of personal data of 25 million people by the tax authorities revealed unimaginable administrative bungling.
A trio of retired generals launched an uprising in the House of Lords in protest against cuts in military spending: being a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the manifold donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's general secretary (and its former head of fulfilment) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably leaving.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a tipping point after which they feel it impossible to govern.
People neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he does not even need to be around for long, this delay is over: the civil service begins to leak; cabinet ministers begin to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would like to deny Tony Blair, he was his first lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction records, for example, are related to decisions made by Brown as chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's misadventures – such as the long "money for nobility" investigation into political party funding – voters may assume it was him.
Still, Brown's situation isn't quite as bad as it looks.
The transgressions are not as terrible as conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely deceived.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The new fuss about political donations is a good example.
The Garboesque Abrahams, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be so, but it was not up to him to decide.
The anonymity laws for big political contributors are clear, and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who rule the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's agreement but not that it was illegal, will of course have to face some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's chief financial collector, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far, Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He was quick to condemn his party's violation of the law, but he watered down that determination by reaching for a familiar instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject -- led, to put it bluntly, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr. Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chair for the independent committee on standards in public life, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a sweeping reform of political party funding.
This would require Labour hardliners to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly abandon the special financial relationship with the trade unions - bitter pills for a party member like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in the opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through unassailable righteousness and solid competence.
Card sharks
Is the credit crisis infecting America's credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is only natural for dorsal fins to swirl around excitedly.
Now that America's real estate market is ailing, the predators have their sights set on the country's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion spreads from underfunded loans to other forms of consumer lending.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both write-offs and delinquency rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are each unrecoverable or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it had taken a $1.4 billion fee collection from its U.S. consumer funding, partly because of weakness in credit card holders.
Still, it's too early to panic.
Losses and defaults are still low.
According to the rating agency Moody, the third-quarter default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in U.S. personal bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to an abrupt fall in bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large portion of credit card losses; the number of applications (and thus late fees) would increase again, whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, showing how much of their debt consumers pay off each month.
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the gridlock in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, expects output volumes for 2007 to ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct channels of infection between the housing credit crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt, now that home equity loans dry up.
However, card issuers look at the cash flow instead of capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be beneficial for the card issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage payments decrease if the real estate is worth less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the stormier conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and completely revalue loans," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's principal finance officer.
Even if a sudden shortfall in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are far more real.
If lower house prices and a credit reduction push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a grimer future.
Keep an eye out for these shark fins.
British bankers plead guilty to Enron case
Three British bankers who were to be tried for their role in the fraudulent scheme with Enron's former chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, changed their petitions to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of telecommunications fraud for allegedly colluding with Fastow in a secret financial fraud in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of their employer.
The trial had been scheduled for January.
But during a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., everyone pleaded guilty to a case of fraud using telecommunications.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, became known in the UK during extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, her case is a loose end to an investigation launched after Enron's collapse in 2001.
The original charges against her in 2002 drew Fastow's attention to the fact that he was the target of a government investigation into the Enron decline.
The indictment against the bankers — dubbed the "NatWest Three" — claims they came to Houston in 2000 to concoct a fraudulent plot with Fastow and his former top adviser Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partnership controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of countless fraudulent Enron schemes that helped drag the company into the vortex of bankruptcy.
In early 2002, the bank had estimated the value of its stake in the subsidiary at zero, but the three British men knew that it actually had substantial value.
A company under Kopper's control acquired the bank's shares in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely argued to Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in fact, the $20 million went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others cashed in about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two conspiracy charges for his role in Enron's bankruptcy.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a 6-year prison sentence in the Louisiana Federal Penitentiary.
Kopper is serving a three-year and one-month sentence at a facility in Texarkana.
Each of the three men was free on $1 million bail that required them to live in the United States awaiting trial.
Enron, once the nation's seventh-largest company, crumbled in bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks could no longer disguise billions in debt or make struggling ventures appear profitable.
The collapse wiped out thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value, and more than $2 billion in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in connection with the Enron collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were overturned after he died last year from heart disease.
Not at the bottom of Moscow
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough range to fly non-stop from Moscow to Los Angeles, is at least $54 million.
But this is small change for some of the rich Russians.
"It can accommodate up to 18 passengers," said Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of you are asking for that many seats because it's for a private family or a company president."
Firer was at the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaires Exhibition, a four-day of flaunted consumption held in a nested exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury vendors had set up exhibition booths, hoping to interest newly-paid Russians in everything from mahogany-paneled yachts to diamond-plated car crickets that would be appropriate for 50 cents.
Firer carefully set his sights on a shiny orange Porsche at the next booth.
"This is a nice car, but it's small change compared to us," he said.
"After the United States, Russia is the second largest market for private aircraft."
Fueled by an oil boom, the Russian capital seems as flooded with money as Dallas did in its heyday.
"We went through the same phase in the 1890s, when some Americans came to gigantic wealth and went in droves to Europe, where they were considered materialistic," said Marshall Goldman, a scholar at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard University.
Like the Saudi high-flyers of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, Russians stand out as the world's most visible generous donors.
The most exclusive luxury brands are seeking their share of the gold rush.
Elsewhere in Moscow, a luxury industry conference this week attracted Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell high-priced goods in markets like Russia.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, owned by The New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires who own a total of $282 billion, according to Forbes' list of the richest people.
In addition, 103,000 Russian millionaires belong to the second class, worth a combined $670 billion, according to a study on the development of private wealth in the former Soviet Union, written by economic experts from the Center for Economic and Financial Research, a panel of experts here.
(The World Bank says that in 2005, 15.8 percent of Russians lived below subsistence level.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow — that's why we're all here," said Nicole Marais, a sales and marketing representative for David Morris, a London-based jeweller.
She had visited the fair for the first time together with the Russian retailer of the brand, the Soho Jewelry Group.
"The women are all groomed in an exemplary manner and the men are all worth a fortune."
As they parade through the halls on Sunday night in evening wear, two real estate agents, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovtsova, 26, refer to themselves and their clients as millionaires.
"I looked at the cars and I'm trying to choose between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche," said Ms. Yumatova, who delivered the designer clothes she wore, like a red carpet veteran with Joan Rivers.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at the nouveau riche, the type of brand-conscious Russian shoppers who would be willing to spend several hours stuck in traffic to visit a draughty warehouse that shamelessly juxtaposed Cadillac Escalades, platinum pocket knives, Mövenpick ice cream, bespoke billiard tables, apartments in Dubai and Gund teddy bears.
The public could buy tickets for 30 euros (44.57 dollars).
"Russians are interested in learning which brand is the most expensive and best," said Mr. Gijrath, who sat patriotically at a booth of Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft in front of a wall-sized imitation of a Rembrandt picture made of hand-painted blue mosaic stones.
"Of course, Russians are more interested in Klimper-Klimper."
In fact, the traders here say that Russians with old money (10-15 years is old by Russian standards) have already moved from ostentatious logos to the kind of sober brands with limited quantities that would not market themselves at a trade show.
Nevertheless, several thousand people, whether millionaires, envoys of millionaires or simply tourists, thronged through the halls every day.
And some of them bought.
On the first night of the show last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the general manager of King Koil beds here, said he had sold two $70,000 mattress sets made of silk, cashmere and cotton, with sewn-in gold threads.
Also on the first night, Mikhail Lyubiumov, a sales manager for A1 Moto, a company that equips high-end cars with high-end alarm systems, said his company had sold the bright orange Porsche to a Russian millionaire for $170,000.
By Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, the president of L.A. Connection, a company that customizes luxury cars to customer requests, said he had sold three car grilles for a Rolls-Royce Phantom that resemble linked chain bangles for $55,000 each.
He showed a reporter a car tire developed for a Russian casino owner, with spokes he had covered with colored Swarovski crystals so that it looked like a roulette wheel.
The cost: $22,000 for a four-set.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather wheels or a picture of his wife's face made of cubic zirconium will not necessarily ride on those wheels," Mr. Karapetian said.
"He'll keep it in his 30- or 40-car garage."
Even though many of his Russian clients are rich, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaires" does not express much exclusivity at the moment, given the rise in local real estate prices.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash," he said.
"There are more of them than you think."
Those who weren't millionaires could at least pretend to be rich at a booth run by Alliance Continental, a Russian asset management company.
The company had set up four red telephone booths based on the British model, which were crammed with mountains of fake million-dollar bills.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing director, said his employees printed 500,000 counterfeit banknotes for the millionaire fair.
Passers-by stopped to throw the piles of money around, have mobile phone photos snapped by friends while they sat back amidst the spare wealth, or simply to pocket a few million.
"You see, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire," Mr. Karryev said.
Botched operation suspected of death in New Jersey
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Ronald Livingston looked through the large glass window of the Just a Little Healthier restaurant here and watched an ambulance stop at the white Cape Cod two doors down West Scott Avenue.
Soon after, there was a police car there.
And then there was another.
"Then I saw the coroner's van approaching," Livingston, a supervisor at the restaurant, said Wednesday.
"That was the point when I knew someone had died."
Authorities learned that the dead woman was Olga Arroyo, 41, an assistant to the director of the Newark Police Department.
Now, investigators are trying to determine if she died because of a procedure performed by an unlicensed cosmetic surgeon that police did not identify and who worked at the house at 212 West Scott Avenue.
Authorities have not yet determined what caused Ms. Arroyo's death, and are hopeful that toxicological investigations, the results of which may not be available for weeks, will help solve a mysterious death that sent grief through the top management of Newark Police.
Ms. Arroyo had been an assistant to Police Director Garry F. McCarthy since September 2006, and her voice was familiar to many in the department.
"She was loyal, hard working and persistent," Mr. McCarthy said of Ms. Arroyo in a telephone interview Wednesday.
"She was my pit bull.
She protected me."
McCarthy said that Ms. Arroyo was the wife of Jimmy Arroyo, a former Newark police officer who works for the Alcohol Control Commission, and that she is survived by two sons, 14 and 11, and a stepdaughter.
Eileen Walsh, a spokeswoman for Union County Procurator Theodore J. Romankow, said investigators are trying to determine whether Arroyo died as a result of unapproved surgical treatment.
"That's one of the possibilities," Ms. Walsh said.
"It's an ongoing investigation."
Authorities said they arrived at the house at about 3 p.m. in November.
And they found Mrs. Arroyo on a sofa.
She was declared dead on the spot.
More than a week has passed and the authorities have said little about their investigation or about the owner of the house, who is listed as Flor Margarita Castro.
Walsh declined to say whether Ms. Castro was questioned by authorities.
Investigators are trying to determine whether part of the house was used as a medical practice.
On Wednesday, no one opened the door to Mrs. Castro's house, where a withered rose bush stands in the narrow front yard and a Dalmatian barks behind the house.
A blue barrel labeled "ethyl vanillin" — used as a substitute for vanilla in food and perfumes — sat in the parking lot next to a door leading to the basement.
Two mountain bikes hung from hooks on one side.
McCarthy said that when he first arrived in Newark after spending 25 years with the New York Police Department, Ms. Arroyo was invaluable and helped him navigate the provincial and harsh political culture in his new city.
"She said, 'You have to pay attention to this or that,'" he said.
"She was always here when I arrived here and she was always here when I left.
It was embarrassing."
Hopes that the central bank will cut interest rates lead to the rise of world stock markets
Stocks jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after market hopes that the central bank will try to calm credit markets by cutting interest rates further were bolstered by soothing comments from the vice chairman of the US Federal Reserve.
Stock markets rose in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kahn, the No. 2 for Ben Bernanke, the chairman of the central bank, said policymakers needed to respond "flexibly and pragmatically" to ongoing pressures in financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm disgruntled markets amid signs of rising credit tensions, Kohn said the recent turmoil had "partially reversed some of the improvements in market functions from late September and October."
If the increased turbulence persists, it would increase the possibility of a further tightening of financial conditions for consumers and businesses, he said.
The comments were taken up by investors as a signal that the central bank is ready to step in and stabilize credit conditions with new capital injections into US markets and possible further interest rate cuts.
The remarks also helped calm Wall Street amid more bad news from the U.S. economy now that U.S. real estate sales hit a new record low in October.
The aftermath of the financial turmoil was underscored by the announcement by Bear Stearns, the investment bank, that it would eliminate 650 jobs, or 4 percent of its global workforce, in a cost-cutting measure to offset heavy losses from its lost bets in the U.S. mortgage lending sector.
Only 20 of these jobs are expected to disappear in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial index jumped 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the broader S&P 500 Index rose 2.65 percent.
In London, the FTSE 100 index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 6,306.2, adding more than £39 billion to the value of UK benchmarks.
Germany's DAX index rose by 2.6 percent and France's CAC40 rose by 2.3 percent.
Earlier, the resurgence of credit pressures on markets was underscored after strong demand was lent at a remarkable 4.7 percent at an auction of three-month guarantee funds from the European Central Bank granted to European commercial banks, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England, the US central bank and the European Central Bank to inject more capital into money markets in London increased as credit tensions saw three-month "Libor" rates for borrowing between UK banks rise to their highest level since late September at 6.59 percent, after a steady increase since November 21.
England faced with decision on the statements of Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara
Here are two dilemmas, each almost as difficult as the other.
Who should beat as number 6 for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, no less relevant in a broader context than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is important because David Graveney, the election chairman, on call at least under this particular title, is here to help head coach Peter Moores and captain Michael Vaughan decide, and because the table of High Morries, the English managing director, is gradually filling up with applications for national electorates, if not part-time.
Whoever doesn't get the sixth bat position will be unhappy, but life is often unfair and the sport undoubtedly is.
It is never easy to pin down exactly what allows a person to reach the top of his profession while someone else never gets beyond the lowest rank, sometimes for lack of luck instead of ability.
It is not only in cricket, where the choice is difficult, where judgments are necessary, which are always subjective in the end.
Is it the right time for Bopara to ascend?
Is it fair to Shah if he does?
The same can perhaps be asked in another area, such as whether John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both intelligent young executives with good degrees who know the business well, should be promoted.
Who can say what the right class is for a cricketer unless he is given the opportunity to swim or sink.
Of course, numbers have a great influence on decisions, but so do opportunities.
Within a team, a cricketer must catch the captain's eye at the right time when he can take a wicket and a racket must be given regular chances on order if he wants to make an impression as a one-day cricketer.
Catching the eyes of the selectors is more complicated.
There were many who were better last season than, for example, when James Anderson, who will apparently play in the first Test, even if Stephen Harmison declares himself healthy and like the wind in the nets.
