I'm inclined to give Bopara his chance now, which doesn't mean that Shah might not look good if, as the tea set from Ceylon suggests, he is the one who will play here this weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and to fight al-Qaeda
The first busloads of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, with a stream of displaced people whose funds or visas have expired and others hoping the city would return to normality.
Some had even returned to fight the rebels who had driven them from their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was busy with refugees from Syria and Jordan returning in private transports.
"I decided to go to Syria after they killed a lot of doctors in Baghdad," said Sabah Al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspaper, about what happened in Baghdad, and how it would be safe now."
They say that the Mahdi Army has stopped killing people," he said, referring to the Shiite militias of militant cleric Moqtada Al-Sadr, who has ordered his forces to be put back for the time being.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher from most of the Sunni part of Amariyah, returned with his two children because he could not renew his Syrian visa and because the regime does not allow Iraqis to work.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him to tell him that a local U.S.-backed militia had helped drive al-Qaeda out of their bastion in the west of the capital and urged him to return.
One of the new arrivals from Jordan was the leader of a Sunni and Shiite tribe who had been driven from his home in Sleikh in northern Baghdad by a hand grenade attack after calling on his fellow citizens to fight al-Qaeda.
He had come back to fight.
"Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they were starting an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my boys.
That's why I came back today," said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
