Venus is Earth's hellish twin
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: The European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it flashes on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided proof - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primordial soup theory", lightning gave rise to life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If ever there was life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, temperatures of 500 degrees sometimes prevail.
"Venus may be Earth's devil twin, but it's a Gemini," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the early nineties no probe has been on the way specifically to explore this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities between our neighbouring planet and Earth are greater than initially assumed," says ESA.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a vortex of clouds at the South Pole that rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves around itself much more slowly: A Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that both planets formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both, which remained in oceans on Earth, but was lost into space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
