After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" stirred up doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes from 1968 a few months ago, internal investigations at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm have now come to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to the Moderna Museet as a gift in 1995, are copies - and probably also the majority of the hundred or so other Brillo boxes of the "Stockholm type",  circulating on the international art market.
The prehistory is convoluted, a confusing concatenation of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red, blue and white design of the cardboard boxes of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of cardboard Brillo boxes: these did not come from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but their role models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time rightly went down in art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have fetched more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at Moderna Museet, examined not only the museum's six Brillo boxes, but also three from Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their pressboard was first primed and sanded off, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressboard with a painter's roll without primer - moreover, it is not oil, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to a different conclusion, Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
In July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious allegations" made in the matter of soap powder boxes.
But since then, they have remained relentlessly silent.
Rebellious soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebellious soldiers who barricaded themselves in a hotel in Manila and called for the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have given up.
He could not answer for bloodshed, said the leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, reporters at the hotel.
Soldiers loyal to the government had previously stormed the hotel using tear gas.
The approximately two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
About half of them were on trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - including Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly defect with around 30 sympathizers.
The military policemen who were supposed to guard him had apparently defected to him and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government troops cordoned off the district around the posh hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' actions.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the elite unit of the Scout Rangers, said other army units would join the march shortly.
Government critics had called for large demonstrations against the president on Friday.
Her government has been overshadowed by allegations of corruption for months.
Manila's financial district was already the main scene of the attempted mutiny of around 200 military personnel against Arroyo in 2003.
The uprising failed after almost 24 hours due to the refusal of the army to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes major shareholder in Versatel
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20 percent in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company announced on Wednesday evening.
It now holds 20.05 percent of the share capital.
There had previously been speculation about a takeover.
One keeps the option open to increase the stake in Versatel.
The move is intended to drive forward the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet announced.
Previously, speculation about an entry had already arisen on Wednesday, after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf-based network operator by a further 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house hold the shares only for a third party, it was said on the financial market.
The day before, United Internet had already acquired a stake of almost 10 percent in the mobile communications company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch placed 17.4 million new shares worth EUR 106.4 million.
United Internet bought 5.15 million of these shares for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have started discussions on marketing cooperations for DSL and mobile products.
"We are strengthening our partnership," said a United Internet spokesperson.
The two companies have created the joint venture MSP to acquire the competitor Freenet.
For the time being, the two companies want to be satisfied with a stake of a good ten percent in Freenet and do not make use of their right to take over another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet announced on Thursday.
However, the two companies kept all options open, in particular to further increase their stake in Freenet AG.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet about a strategic partnership ended in mid-November.
The poker game over Freenet, which has been going on for months and is difficult to understand, is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million mobile contract customers and 1.27 million DSL and full-line customers.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch previously held 6.01 percent of the Freenet shares.
Now it has been agreed that Drillisch brings in another four percent.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent from the investment company Vatas had already been agreed in August.
